{"questionId":"21970","questionHtml":"<p>A triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> with vertices lying on the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></math> plane is transformed by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>Explain why both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> and its image will have exactly the same area.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>det</mtext><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>7</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">OR</mtext><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mrow><mtext>det </mtext><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>7</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>scale factor of image area is therefore <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mn>1</mn></math> (and the translation does not affect the area) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21970","referenceCode":"21M.1.AHL.TZ2.14c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"A triangle L with vertices lying on the xy plane is transformed by T. Explain why both L and its image will have exactly the same area.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum ma